---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout seoSlug="/woocommerce-affiliate-program-guide">
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="eyebrow">★ STEP-BY-STEP GUIDE · 2026</div>
    <h1>How to start a <span class="accent">WooCommerce affiliate program</span></h1>
    <p class="lead">Launching an affiliate program for your WooCommerce store takes 5 steps: install a plugin, set commission rates, create a sign-up page, recruit your first affiliates, and pay out. With a self-hosted approach you keep full control of your affiliate data; with a SaaS approach you pay monthly forever for someone else to host it.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="intro">
    <div class="intro-inner">
      <h2>What a WooCommerce affiliate program actually does for your store</h2>
      <p>An affiliate program is a fixed-margin trade: you give bloggers, influencers, podcasters and existing customers a unique tracking link, and you pay them a percentage of any sale that originates from their link. The customer-acquisition cost is zero up-front — you pay only after a sale closes and only on the order that was attributed. For most WooCommerce stores, an affiliate program ends up being the single highest-ROI customer-acquisition channel after email, because the cost is post-revenue and capped at whatever commission rate you set.</p>
      <p>The plumbing — tracking links, cookie attribution, commission calculation, payouts, fraud checks, affiliate dashboards — is what an affiliate plugin handles. This guide walks through the five steps to launch an in-house program on your own WooCommerce store, with notes on what the major plugins do at each step and where the trade-offs sit.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="steps">
    <div class="steps-inner">
      <h2>The 5 steps</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><h3>1. Choose a plugin</h3><p>Self-hosted: AffiliateWP, SliceWP, Solid Affiliate, Asteris Affiliates. SaaS: Tapfiliate, Rewardful. <a href="/best-woocommerce-affiliate-plugin">Comparison →</a></p></li>
        <li><h3>2. Set commission rates</h3><p>10–20% is standard for digital products; 5–10% for physical. Per-product overrides for high-margin items.</p></li>
        <li><h3>3. Create a sign-up page</h3><p>Most plugins ship a [shortcode] or block that renders the sign-up form. Approve manually or auto-approve.</p></li>
        <li><h3>4. Recruit affiliates</h3><p>Existing customers, niche bloggers, podcast hosts, micro-influencers. Provide swipe-copy, banners, vanity links.</p></li>
        <li><h3>5. Pay out</h3><p>Monthly batch via PayPal API or bank transfer. Set a minimum threshold ($50 or $100 is common).</p></li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="deep">
    <div class="deep-inner">
      <h2>Step 1 in depth — choosing the plugin</h2>
      <p>The two real choices are self-hosted (a WordPress plugin) or SaaS (a hosted tracker that injects a JS snippet on your checkout). For WooCommerce-centric stores, self-hosted wins on cost, data ownership, and page-load weight. SaaS wins if you're tracking across multiple non-WP carts simultaneously and need one consolidated dashboard. <a href="/best-woocommerce-affiliate-plugin">Side-by-side comparison of the 6 most-shopped plugins →</a></p>
      <p>Within self-hosted, the choice comes down to feature set vs price. AffiliateWP is the established option at $299–$599/yr base, with most advanced features behind paid add-ons. SliceWP Pro is the lightweight option at $299/yr base, with no MLM at any tier. Asteris Affiliates is $149/yr Starter with the full stack in core — MLM, AI swipe-copy, cloud-assist fraud, Stripe Connect, Surecart adapter. <a href="/affiliatewp-vs-asteris">AffiliateWP vs Asteris →</a></p>

      <h2>Step 2 in depth — setting commission rates</h2>
      <p>Three rate-setting approaches and when each makes sense:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Single flat rate (10–20% on digital, 5–10% on physical):</strong> simplest, easiest to communicate. Works for stores with broadly similar margins across the catalogue.</li>
        <li><strong>Per-product rates:</strong> set a different rate per product. High-margin items can pay 25–30%; loss-leaders can pay 2%. Asteris ships this in core; AffiliateWP requires the Tiered Affiliate Rates add-on.</li>
        <li><strong>Per-affiliate rates:</strong> negotiate custom rates with top performers. Standard rate for everyone else, override for the 5% of affiliates driving 50% of the revenue. Every major plugin supports this on the affiliate edit screen.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Two-tier (MLM) is a separate consideration: if you want affiliates to earn 5–10% on sub-affiliates they recruit (compounding referrals), you need a plugin that supports it. Asteris includes it from Starter; AffiliateWP requires the MLM add-on.</p>

      <h2>Step 3 in depth — the sign-up flow</h2>
      <p>The default sign-up flow on most plugins is a form with email, name, payout-method preference, and optional bio/website. Two patterns to choose between:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Manual approval (recommended for most stores):</strong> every applicant goes to a "pending" queue. You review name/website/email, approve the relevant ones, reject obvious spam. Catches the fraud waves automated programs miss.</li>
        <li><strong>Auto-approval:</strong> anyone who fills the form becomes an affiliate immediately. Higher signup volume, much higher fraud rate. Only sensible if you also have aggressive fraud detection (IP throttling + cloud-assist) and a low payout threshold that holds 30+ days.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Asteris ships a 4-step onboarding wizard that captures payout method (Stripe Connect / PayPal / bank transfer) and tax preferences during signup, so your first payout run isn't blocked by missing details.</p>

      <h2>Step 4 in depth — recruiting your first affiliates</h2>
      <p>The five sources that work for almost every WooCommerce store, in priority order:</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Existing satisfied customers</strong> — email everyone who's bought in the last 12 months and given a positive review. Highest conversion-to-affiliate rate of any source. Use a custom email to your customer list, not a public landing page.</li>
        <li><strong>Niche bloggers and content creators</strong> who already mention your product category. Search Google for "<em>your category</em> review" and reach out to anyone in the first 3 pages. Offer slightly above your standard rate for top-tier bloggers — a 20% rate negotiable to 25% for proven traffic.</li>
        <li><strong>Podcast hosts</strong> in adjacent niches. Sponsorships are expensive; an affiliate link with a discount code is often more attractive to a podcaster than a flat sponsor fee.</li>
        <li><strong>Micro-influencers</strong> on Instagram/TikTok in your customer demographic. 5K–50K followers convert better than 500K because the audience is tighter.</li>
        <li><strong>Industry forums and Slack communities</strong> — quietly become known as helpful, mention your store in your signature, share an affiliate code for community members.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>Give affiliates ready-to-go materials: vanity <code>{`/go/{handle}`}</code> landing pages, swipe-copy snippets for emails, image banners in 3–4 standard ad sizes, FAQ docs. The lower the friction to promote, the more they'll promote. Asteris ships the swipe-copy generator (16 seed snippets + AI variants), vanity landing pages and image-banner upload in core.</p>

      <h2>Step 5 in depth — payouts</h2>
      <p>Three payout-method options and the trade-offs:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Stripe Connect Express (lowest fee, fastest, recommended):</strong> affiliates onboard via Stripe's hosted flow, payouts settle direct to their bank, Stripe takes 0.25%. Only Asteris ships this for affiliate payouts in the WordPress ecosystem currently.</li>
        <li><strong>PayPal Payouts API (2% fee, broadest coverage):</strong> works in most countries PayPal does, charges 2% per payout (capped at $1 in some markets). Asteris ships OAuth2 batch payouts in core; AffiliateWP requires the PayPal Payouts add-on.</li>
        <li><strong>Bank transfer with bank-CSV export:</strong> generate a CSV in your bank's format (AU + US supported), upload to your business bank's batch-payment system. No third-party fees, but more manual. Asteris ships AU NAB/CBA/ANZ/Westpac and US ACH NACHA formats.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Set a minimum payout threshold ($50–$100 is standard) and a payout cadence (monthly is most common, weekly for high-volume programs, quarterly if you want lower payout overhead).</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="more">
    <div class="more-inner">
      <h2>The commission-rate maths most stores get wrong</h2>
      <p>Affiliates typically negotiate on commission rate, and stores typically panic-cut rates after a few months because the program "feels expensive." Both moves are usually mistakes — driven by looking at gross commission cost rather than net acquisition cost. Run the comparison properly:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Your current customer acquisition cost (CAC)</strong> across paid ads, content, SEO and email. For most WooCommerce stores in 2026 this lands somewhere between 15–40% of first-order revenue.</li>
        <li><strong>Your effective affiliate CAC</strong> is the commission rate (typically 10–20%) plus the cost of running the program (tracking plugin licence + your time managing the program, amortised across all affiliate-driven orders).</li>
        <li><strong>If the affiliate program's effective CAC is lower than your paid-channel CAC,</strong> you should be doing more affiliate marketing, not less. Cutting the commission rate when affiliates are out-performing ads is solving the wrong problem.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The honest framing: an affiliate program isn't a discount you give away. It's a sales channel with capped, post-revenue acquisition cost. The cap is the commission rate. If the channel works, the bill grows — but every dollar of that bill is tied to a dollar of revenue that wouldn't have come in otherwise.</p>

      <h2>The fraud problem most new programs underestimate</h2>
      <p>Within 30 days of launching an affiliate program with auto-approval enabled, expect at least one of these patterns:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Self-referral fraud:</strong> someone signs up as an affiliate, buys your product themselves through their own affiliate link, then refunds the order after the commission credits. Asteris ships 5-pattern self-referral detection in core (user-ID match, email match, payout-detail match, IP match, cookie match).</li>
        <li><strong>Coupon stacking:</strong> an affiliate-linked discount code gets shared on coupon-aggregator sites, customers who would have bought anyway use it, and the affiliate harvests commissions on traffic they didn't actually drive. Mitigate with attribution rules that require non-discount-referrer traffic, or with affiliate-specific landing pages that the coupon site can't easily extract from.</li>
        <li><strong>Cookie-stuffing:</strong> shady affiliates inject your tracking cookie via iframe or redirect on any site visitor, hoping some percentage will later buy organically. Mitigate with first-click-only attribution (rather than last-click), and with affiliate-portal click-pattern analysis that flags affiliates with click-to-conversion ratios well outside the program average.</li>
        <li><strong>Account takeover:</strong> an affiliate's account gets compromised and the attacker changes the payout email to their own. Mitigate with email-change notifications, payout-detail change cool-down periods (Asteris defaults to 48 hours), and 2FA on affiliate accounts (Asteris supports any WordPress 2FA plugin).</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The Asteris cloud-assist fraud detection layer (opt-in, SHA-256 hashed) shares fraud-pattern signals across stores running Asteris, so new stores benefit from the lessons every prior store learned. Disable it and you still get the per-store detection layers; enable it and you get the network-effect overlay.</p>

      <h2>What "good" affiliate-program performance looks like</h2>
      <p>Rough benchmarks that hold across most WooCommerce store categories. Use them as a sanity check on your program, not as targets:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Affiliate-driven revenue as a percent of total:</strong> 5–15% is typical for a mature program. Programs above 20% are doing something genuinely well; programs below 3% after a year are either under-recruited or have a product affiliates don't have a natural channel to recommend.</li>
        <li><strong>Affiliate-to-conversion ratio:</strong> healthy programs see 1–5% of affiliate clicks convert. Below 0.5% suggests poor traffic quality; above 8% suggests possible cookie-stuffing or pre-converted traffic.</li>
        <li><strong>Top-20% of affiliates driving 80% of revenue:</strong> almost universal. Identify the top 20% and invest in them — custom rates, dedicated swipe-copy support, occasional bonuses. The bottom 50% will either churn or stay dormant; don't spend energy converting them.</li>
        <li><strong>Average affiliate lifespan:</strong> 6–18 months for active affiliates. Plan for renewal — annual program refreshes, new creatives, new commission structures keep the active list engaged.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="faq">
    <div class="faq-inner">
      <h2>FAQ</h2>
      <details><summary>How do I start a WooCommerce affiliate program?</summary><p>Install an affiliate plugin, set your commission rate, create an affiliate sign-up page, approve affiliates and pay commissions on completed orders.</p></details>
      <details><summary>Do I need a SaaS service?</summary><p>No. A self-hosted plugin keeps the program and data inside your own WordPress.</p></details>
      <details><summary>What commission rate should I offer?</summary><p>10–20% on digital products, 5–10% on physical goods, depending on margin. Increase for top performers via per-product overrides.</p></details>
      <details><summary>How do I avoid affiliate fraud?</summary><p>Per-IP throttling, cookie + IP attribution, and (in Asteris Affiliates) optional cloud-assist fraud signal sharing across stores.</p></details>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cta-section">
    <div class="cta-inner">
      <h2>Run the program in your own WordPress</h2>
      <p>Asteris Affiliates: self-hosted, two-tier included, $149/yr.</p>
      <a href="/pricing" class="btn btn-pop btn-large">See pricing →</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

